A deposit was required, and the balance due at delivery.</div></div><hr />


<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Alikat Astrae</div><div class="date">December 13th, 2004, 12:54 PM</div></div><div class="posttext">The trick is to have 5 or six of your meanest-looking friends there to greet the truck driver on arrival.  If he tries to inflate the price, beat the living crap out of him and unload the truck yourselves, then pay him what you agreed on and inform him that this was &quot;just a taste&quot; of what he has coming to him if you ever so much as hear his name ever again.  For bonus points you can keep the truck driver and his partners in a set of giant glass jars in your basement, and feed them nothing but stale double-stuff Oreos.  Or, you could skin the truck driver, and wear the truck driver's skin, and use the truck driver's skin as a gateway to another dimension....</div></div><hr />


<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Khaymus</div><div class="date">December 13th, 2004, 03:25 PM</div></div><div class="posttext">First, demand a detailed invoice for services rendered and what they based their estimate on.<br />
<br />
Second, consult a lawyer if you have not already done so. Low-balling an estimate to get a job and jacking the price up by ~350% after they've picked up the order borders on fraud.<br />
<br />
I wouldn't report the money order stolen...you could get into trouble yourself for fraud or perjury since you usually have to sign an affidavit to that effect. Disputing the credit card charge would definitely be an option though and would require the company to justify the charge and your estimate is likely to hold a lot more weight with the CC company that with the moving company. You'll also have a company with larger resources than you have going to bat for you.</div></div><hr />


